On 
Monday, the caskets of Ross, Larche and Gevaudan were on display inside 
the Wesleyan Celebration Centre for seven hours so visitors could pay 
their respects. They were greeted by six Canadian mounties, with two 
mounties guardian each casket.

Each
 casket was covered in the Canadian flag. On top of each caskets a 
Canadian stetson hat was perched, along with a gun holster.

Next to the caskets were images of the officers in their uniforms, as well as photos of them on the job in Moncton.

Ross,
 Larche and Gevaudan were killed in a shooting spree allegedly committed
 by Justin Bourque, 24. Bourque also allegedly shot and injured two 
other officers, who survived.

Bourque was apprehended by authorities after a 30-hour manhunt that effectively shut Moncton down. He has been charged with three counts of first-degree murder, as well as two counts of attempted murder.

